==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*sinþ''.  Cognate with Old Saxon ''sīþ'', Old High German [[sind]], [[sint]], Old Norse [[sinn]] (Icelandic [[sinn]], [[sinni]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌹𐌽𐌸𐍃]].  The root is a variant of the ancestor of [[sendan]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /si:θ/

===Noun===
'''sīþ''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''sīþas''')
# a [[journey]], a [[movement]]
#:''Brim berstende blodegesan hweop sæmanna sið'': the bursting ocean had threatened the seamen’s journey with blood-fear.  (''Junius Exodus'')
# a [[time]] or [[occasion]]
#:''ða wæs forma sið deorum madme þæt his dom alæg'': that was the first time for the precious treasure that its renown failed.  (''Beowulf 1527'')

